In 1950 [[Finland]]'s first '''Municipal Homemaking Act''' ({{lang-fi|Laki kunnallisista kodinhoitajista}}, 272/1950<ref>http://www.finlex.fi/fi/laki/smur/1950/19500272</ref>) was passed.<ref name="Bergman1989">{{cite book|author=Solveig Bergman|title=Women's Worlds: Finnish Contributions to the Third International Interdisciplinary Congress on Women, Dublin, 1987|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KV0yAAAAIAAJ|year=1989|pages=55|publisher=Institute of Women's Studies at Åbo Akademi University|isbn=978-951-649-573-9}}</ref><ref name="Cheal2003">{{cite book|author=David Cheal|title=Family: Critical Concepts in Sociology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sAYy_oEw6NcC&pg=PA360|year=2003|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-22631-8|pages=360–}}</ref> [[Miina Sillanpää]] was involved in its preparation.<ref name="CorrJamieson1990">{{cite book|author1=Helen Corr|author2=Lynn Jamieson|author3=Karin Gwinn Wilkins|title=State Private Life And Political Change|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DE6xCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA125|date=22 May 1990|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn=978-1-349-20707-7|pages=125-}}</ref> The system of municipal [[homemaking|homemakers]] was created to help rural families with some children who lived in poverty.<ref name="2CorrJamieson1990">{{cite book|author1=Helen Corr|author2=Lynn Jamieson|author3=Karin Gwinn Wilkins|title=State Private Life And Political Change|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DE6xCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA125&lpg=PA126&dq=%22municipal+homemaking+act%22&source=bl&ots=q79npdpipT&sig=SVtN3Ecti31MO9wEZGhiBaJs4TA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi7z-XCjpTPAhXNZj4KHXM7AQIQ6AEIIjAC#v=onepage&q=%22%22from%20the%20beginning%20homemakers%22&f=false|date=22 May 1990|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn=978-1-349-20707-7|pages=126–}}</ref> The municipal homemakers had their salaries paid by the [[municipality]].<ref name="2CorrJamieson1990"/>
